            I shall leave aside proper considerations about the stewardship of the countryside, the maintenance of the rural landscape, the environment and wildlife habitats&#x2014;all those things&#x2014;to ask the hon. Gentleman a simple question. The smaller proportion of their income that people now spend on food does not go largely to farmers. The great bulk of the food price is absorbed by other elements of the food chain, as he surely knows. Is he defending that? Is he the ally of the so-called greedy corporate bosses that other members of his party so condemn?
          </p>
